B. Support account posts
Actions to be taken by the General Assembly
The actions to be taken by the General Assembly are as follows:
(a) To approve the support account estimate amounting to $51,736,600 gross ($44,189,100 net) for the period from 1 July 2000 to 30 June 2001;
(b) To apply the unencumbered balance of $2,179,400 from the period from 1 July 1998 to 30 June 1999 (inclusive of $601,000 in miscellaneous and interest income) to the resources required for the period from 1 July 2000 to 30 June 2001;
(c) To prorate the balance of $49,557,200 gross among the individual active peacekeeping operation budgets to meet the requirements of the support account for the period from 1 July 2000 to 30 June 2001.
Developments in the current period
Following its consideration of the report of the Secretary-General of 4 March 1999 (A/53/854/Add.1) and the related report of the Advisory Committee on Administrative and Budgetary Questions (A/53/901), the General Assembly in resolution 53/12 B of 8 June 1999 approved resources in the amount of $34,887,100 for the support account for peacekeeping operations for the period from 1 July 1999 to 30 June 2000, including 400 posts.
In his report, the Secretary-General indicated that, at the time of formulating his proposals, the number of peacekeeping missions had decreased from 16 to 14 and the estimated total budget level for the period from 1 July 1998 to 30 June 1999 amounted to some $843 million.
For the period from 1 July 1999 to 30 June 2000, the initial total estimated budget level for all peacekeeping operations, including the support account, was estimated at that stage to be around $650 million.
Although this figure was lower than the gross apportionment for the period from 1 July 1998 to 30 June 1999, it was pointed out that the actual 1999/00 requirement could increase significantly if new peacekeeping missions were established as a result of ongoing peace initiatives in conflict areas.
In that connection, the Secretary-General would request additional resources should the need arise.
Subsequently, by its resolution 1244 (1999) of 10 June 1999, the Security Council established the United Nations Interim Administration Mission in Kosovo (UNMIK). The unprecedented complex and multifaceted tasks facing UNMIK cover a wide range of specialities ranging from health, education and prison administration to the establishment of a judiciary and a local police force, all of which require specialized backstopping from Headquarters.
On 22 October 1999, in its resolution 1270 (1999), the Security Council established the United Nations Mission in Sierra Leone (UNAMSIL) and decided that it would take over the substantive civilian and military components of the United Nations Observer Mission in Sierra Leone (UNOMSIL).
The follow-on mission UNAMSIL entailed deployment of 5,740 military contingent personnel and the emplacement of 50 additional military observers.
Subsequently, in its resolution 1289 (2000) of 7 February 2000, the Council authorized a further increase in military personnel for UNAMSIL up to 11,100.
On the same day, in its resolution 1271 (1999), the Security Council decided to extend the mandate of the United Nations Mission in the Central African Republic (MINURCA) until 15 February 2000 following the presidential elections.
On 25 October 1999, the Security Council established in its resolution 1272 (1999) the United Nations Transitional Administration in East Timor (UNTAET) with overall responsibility for the administration of the Territory and empowered to exercise all legislative and executive authority, including the administration of justice.
The Mission also included a military and police component of up to 8,950 military contingent personnel, 1,640 civilian police and 200 military observers.
In its resolutions 1258 (1999) of 6 August 1999 and 1279 (1999) of 30 November 1999, the Security Council, inter alia, established the United Nations Organization Mission in the Congo (MONUC), which involved initial deployment of 90 military liaison personnel and 134 civilian personnel.
It requested the Secretary-General to take the administrative steps necessary for the equipping of up to 500 United Nations military observers with a view to facilitating future rapid United Nations deployment as authorized by the Council.
Subsequently, by its resolution 1291 (2000) of 24 February 2000, the Council authorized the expansion of MONUC to consist of up to 5,537 military personnel and appropriate civilian support staff.
In its resolution 1273 (1999) of 5 November 1999, the Council requested the Secretary-General to continue to report regularly on developments in the Democratic Republic of the Congo, including on the future presence of the United Nations in the country in support of the peace process.
The rapid developments described in paragraphs 7 to 12 above had, by 31 December 1999, increased the budget level for all peacekeeping operations for the current period, 1 July 1999 to 30 June 2000, to some $1.4 billion.
Further financing actions that are expected to be taken by the General Assembly in the remaining months of the period will increase this overall level to about $2 billion.
It was on the basis of those developments (see paras.
7 to 13 above) that the Secretary-General on 10 December 1999, submitted a further report (A/54/648) containing revised requirements for the support account for the period from 1 July 1999 to 30 June 2000.
Following its consideration of the report and the related report of the Advisory Committee on Administrative and Budgetary Questions (A/54/661), the General Assembly on 23 December 1999 approved the establishment of 67 new posts for the period ending 30 June 2000 (resolution 54/243).
In the same resolution, the Assembly authorized the Secretary-General to enter into commitments not exceeding $3,501,600 for the additional staff costs, and requested that he report to the Assembly on the actual additional resource requirements in the context of the performance report for the period from 1 July 1999 to 30 June 2000.
For the next period from 1 July 2000 to 30 June 2001, despite the completion of four peacekeeping operations (MONUA, the United Nations Civilian Police Mission in Haiti (MIPONUH), MINURCA and the United Nations Mission of Observers in Tajikistan (UNMOT)), the total budget level for all peacekeeping operations is expected to be at least $2 billion.
Unfinished work on old as well as recently closed/completed missions also continues.
Firstly, it is pertinent to note that among the striking features of the new missions to be backstopped are the complexity of their mandates and the large numbers of civilian personnel who, by definition, are not part of formed military units.
Complex mandates constitute a more rigorous challenge, involving a broader range of expertise, to plan operations, to provide them with guidance and to ensure system-wide coordination.
Since many of the areas of expertise involved have never before been part of peacekeeping, it has been necessary to develop new conceptual and practical frameworks for their involvement.
The recruitment of civilians must be conducted on an individual, post-by-post basis, and missions with a larger proportion of civilians require much greater per capita administrative and logistical support than an infantry battalion, for example, which is to some degree self-contained.
A. Rapidly deployable mission headquarters
In its resolutions 53/12 A of 26 October 1998 and 53/12 B of 8 June 1999, the General Assembly requested that a comprehensive review be undertaken of a rapidly deployable mission headquarters.
In its report of 22 June 1995 (A/50/230), the Special Committee on Peacekeeping Operations had urged the Secretary-General to develop a rapidly deployable headquarters team composed of personnel skilled in essentially military and civilian headquarters functions.
The General Assembly had endorsed that recommendation in its resolution 50/30 dated 6 December 1995.
The rapidly deployable mission headquarters was to consist of three tiers.
The first tier would include a core team of eight personnel, consisting of six military officers, one civilian police officer and one humanitarian affairs officer.
This team would be stationed in the Department of Peacekeeping Operations, on stand-by and ready for deployment within seven days of the establishment of a peacekeeping operation.
It would provide to the head of mission an immediate capacity to direct the military and civilian police aspects of the mission, and for liaison with the humanitarian community in the mission area.
The second tier, comprising 29 United Nations political, logistic and administrative Secretariat staff, would be deployed within 14 days of the establishment of an operation.
The third tier, comprising 24 military and administrative/logistic personnel, earmarked by Member States and serving in their home countries, would be deployed within 28 days of the establishment of a mission.
Funding for the rapidly deployable mission headquarters was to come from a trust fund established for that purpose.
In his report of 20 March 1998 (A/52/837 and Corr.1), the Secretary-General informed the General Assembly that voluntary funding at a level necessary to establish the rapidly deployable mission headquarters had not been forthcoming and recommended that the first tier of eight posts be funded under the support account budget.
Subsequently, under its resolution 53/12 A, the General Assembly approved the establishment of two posts for the headquarters, namely the civilian police officer and the humanitarian officer, and requested that the other six posts be provided through the redeployment of existing support account financed Secretariat positions.
In the same resolution, the Assembly requested the Secretary-General to undertake a comprehensive review of the headquarters.
It was not possible to provide the six additional posts for the headquarters through redeployment within the existing support account resources.
In view of the renewed expansion of peacekeeping activities over the past year, the need for a mechanism to ensure the rapid deployment of peacekeeping personnel has become even more acute.
At the same time, recent experience shows that the type of personnel needed to establish a peacekeeping operation has changed, because the nature of peacekeeping itself has evolved.
The Secretariat has undertaken the present review in the light of the recent evolution of peacekeeping and with a view to making the rapidly deployable mission headquarters concept more applicable to current needs.
For the most part, peacekeeping operations today are involved in the settlement of civil conflicts in areas where the structures of government administration have often been severely weakened or destroyed.
In building an enabling environment for peace, such operations must address a wide range of issues.
They must also be deployed quickly in order to avoid the creation of a security and administrative vacuum, which could be filled by undesirable elements.
Today's peacekeeping operations, including those established in the past year (UNMIK, UNTAET, UNAMSIL and MONUC), contain significant political, military, civilian police and civil administration components, mandated to implement core tasks that must begin upon the establishment of an operation.
In this connection, while the military continues to play an essential role in providing security, on the basis of which other activities can take place, the role of the civilian police and civilian expertise has evolved and become increasingly central in the implementation of peacekeeping mandates.
In recent years, the authorized strength of civilian police in peacekeeping has grown from 2,400 in 1995 to nearly 9,000 in 2000.
Their role has also evolved from one of essentially monitoring local police forces to include such functions as training and assisting in the establishment of local police forces, border policing and, in some cases, executive responsibility for law and order.
As police are maintained by Governments on an individual basis and not, like the military, as formed units, it can be very difficult to identify and deploy them quickly.
In many areas, peacekeeping operations today also involve the strengthening of local institutions and, in some cases, responsibility for transitional administrations.
As a result, the number of civilian staff serving peacekeeping operations has grown from some 8,400 in 1995 to over 12,500 in 2000.
The expertise required to carry out civilian tasks includes, inter alia, experienced personnel in the governance of local and State-level administrations and services.
Expertise is also required to set up and run: budgetary and fiscal systems; public utilities and the health and education sectors; judiciary systems (including judges, lawyers, prison guards); demobilization, human rights and humanitarian assistance programmes, etc. Such expertise is found in national and local governments, United Nations specialized agencies and, but not, for the most part, in the United Nations Secretariat.
Furthermore, such personnel must be deployed quickly in order to avoid a vacuum in the administration of an area, which can lead to instability and insecurity.
Hence, profiles of potentially required personnel, and organizations where such expertise can be found, must be developed in advance of the establishment of an operation.
Another critical element for rapid deployment is administration and logistic personnel, including certifying officers, without which a mission cannot function.
Given the nature of United Nations peacekeeping and the methods and procedures of the Organization, only experienced personnel can be deployed during the first phase of the establishment of a mission.
Of course, all of these tasks are under the overall leadership of a special representative of the Secretary-General and are carried out in support of an overall peace process.
It goes without saying that the senior political leadership of a mission, and their essential political support staff, must also be the first elements of deployment in order to consolidate the peace process in its first critical days and to provide overall leadership for the mission.
As illustrated above, the original concept of the rapidly deployable mission headquarters, which assumed that only one mission at a time would be established and included only a limited range of expertise, clearly does not meet the requirements of today's peacekeeping operations.
The Secretariat has, therefore, decided to adjust the concept of the rapidly deployable mission headquarters with the objective of ensuring the rapid deployment of a wide variety of expertise, including military.
The revised system for rapid deployment would utilize the expertise of the United Nations Secretariat and system of agencies and programmes, Member States and non-governmental organizations.
It would include political, military, civilian police and a broad range of civilian experts and logistic and administrative personnel.
Given the multifunctional expertise required, responsibility for the system would be directly under the Under-Secretary-General for Peacekeeping Operations. The modus operandi of the system would be based on arrangements with Member States and relevant organizations for the immediate release, upon the establishment of a peacekeeping operation, of individually pre-selected personnel, who would be deployed for a period of 60 to 90 days.
They would be replaced by more permanent personnel as soon as they could be deployed.
Political personnel.
A decision on the senior political leadership of a mission is made at the highest levels of the United Nations.
As noted above, they must be deployed quickly to consolidate the peace and provide overall leadership and direction for the mission.
Their political staff, who would usually come from within the Secretariat and ongoing peacekeeping operations, must also be deployed quickly in order to support them in this work.
This would also include public information and legal personnel.
Such personnel would be pre-selected for deployment within seven days of the establishment of an operation and would remain in the mission for 60 to 90 days.
A pool of back-up personnel would also be pre-selected to carry out their functions on a temporary basis during their absence.
Military personnel.
The task of the military personnel, who would be immediately deployed, would be to establish a military headquarters and translate broad strategic-level concepts of military operations and plans developed by the Department of Peacekeeping Operations into concrete operational and tactical level orders and instructions.
In order to operate effectively upon deployment, these personnel must have had prior experience as staff officers in United Nations peacekeeping operations or at Headquarters.
It is envisaged that such personnel, working in their national capacity, would be put on standby to be deployed within seven days of the establishment of a peacekeeping operation.
The Secretariat would enter into such arrangements with a number of Member States, thus having the capacity to deploy quickly to more than one mission at a time.
As with military personnel, civilian police personnel experienced in United Nations peacekeeping operations, would be put on standby for deployment within seven days of the establishment of a peacekeeping mandate.
The standby roster would include a number of civilian police specialties.
Again, the Secretariat would seek to enter into such arrangements with a number of Member States, thus having the capacity to deploy quickly to more than one mission at a time.
Civil administration.
Based on past experience, it is envisaged that some 30 separate types of skills may be required depending on the mandate of a particular mission.
Some, but not all, areas of expertise would be immediately required.
In order to ensure the quick deployment of such personnel, the Department of Peacekeeping Operations would develop profiles of expertise required.
Such expertise would come from Member States, international organizations, non-governmental organizations, United Nations agencies and programmes and the international financial institutions.
The necessary experts would be identified in advance and arrangements would be worked out with their parent organizations/ Member States for deployment within seven days of the establishment of a peacekeeping operation.
Administrative and logistics personnel.
As noted above, this category of personnel would usually come from within the Secretariat and ongoing United Nations peacekeeping operations.
It is envisaged that such personnel would be identified in advance and would be ready to be deployed within seven days of the establishment of a peacekeeping operation.
In order to maintain the required capacity in the Secretariat and ongoing missions upon their deployment, a back-up arrangement would be established whereby their functions would be filled on a temporary basis from a pool of pre-selected personnel.
It is envisaged that a small unit would be established in the office of the Under-Secretary-General for Peacekeeping Operations that would be responsible for setting up the new system and ensuring that it functioned effectively.
The Rapid Deployment Management Unit would: (a) establish or refine profiles of personnel required to carry out the full range of tasks necessary to launch any type of peacekeeping operation that might be established by the Security Council; (b) develop and oversee a system for the pre-selection of standby personnel (roster of rapidly deployable personnel); (c) consult with Member States and various organizations in identifying necessary personnel, and develop the appropriate administrative arrangements for their rapid deployment; and (d) monitor emerging requirements and adjust the roster of rapidly deployable personnel to ensure that such needs can be met.
Under the revised rapid deployment concept, the Rapid Deployment Management Unit would comprise four posts: head of office (P-5), humanitarian officer (P-4), civilian police officer (P-4) and one General Service staff.
The P-5 and General Service post represent new posts to be provided in the context of the support account for peacekeeping operations for the period commencing 1 July 2000.
Further details regarding this proposal are provided in paragraph 65 below.
In carrying out its functions, the Rapid Deployment Management Unit would work closely with focal points in the Office of Operations, Military and Civilian Police Division, and the Field Administrative Logistics Division.
In the weeks leading up to the establishment of a potential mission, the Rapid Deployment Management Unit would work particularly closely with the concerned units in the Department of Peacekeeping Operations to identify immediate personnel requirements and select personnel from the roster.
As much advance notification as possible would be provided to participating Member States and organizations for the release of personnel.
Nevertheless, it would be clearly understood by all participating in the programme that, in some cases, the United Nations might have very little lead-time to prepare for an operation and, consequently, in such cases the notification period might be extremely tight.
Each participating Member State and organization would be responsible for ensuring that pre-selected staff were kept in a high state of readiness for immediate deployment.
In this connection, a key element in the success of the system would be the conclusion of a binding memorandum of understanding with each participating partner to ensure that staff on the rapid deployment roster were in fact available and ready to be deployed when needed.
Staff selected for possible rapid deployment would continue to perform their current functions when their presence in the field was not required.
In establishing the roster, every effort would be made to include personnel from as wide a geographic range as possible, as well as female candidates.
Under the new concept of rapid deployment, there would be a requirement for appropriate training and familiarization of the personnel involved.
This requirement would be examined by the Rapid Deployment Management Unit and cost-effective means of training and familiarization established.
In requesting a review of the rapidly deployable mission headquarters, the General Assembly specifically requested that it address the following: (a) the difference between the responsibilities of the rapidly deployable mission headquarters and those of the Military Planning Service; (b) further develop the concept of the rapidly deployable mission headquarters; (c) the Advisory Committee on Administrative and Budgetary Questions' comments on fragmented planning processes in the Department of Peacekeeping Operations as they relate to the original rapidly deployable mission headquarters concept; and (d) examine the possibility of filling required posts through redeployment of existing support account established posts throughout the Secretariat.
In its report of 6 April 1999 (A/53/901), the Advisory Committee noted that the Secretary-General's report of 4 March 1999 (A/53/854) had clarified the roles of the Military Planning Service and the rapidly deployable mission headquarters, but noted the potential for duplication in the areas of training and planning.
In the Secretary-General's report, it was noted that the primary responsibility of the Military Planning Service was to provide advice on the tasks and possible configuration of military components of new peacekeeping missions and to develop the related concept of operations.
The responsibility of the rapidly deployable mission headquarters, on the other hand, would be to prepare the more detailed plans that were normally established by the military headquarters in the field.
For example, it would translate the strategic-level military concept of operations and the outline plan prepared by the Department of Peacekeeping Operations into operational and tactical-level orders and instructions, including detailed tasking to those who would implement the orders.
Under the revised rapid deployment system, those tasks would also be carried out upon immediate deployment by military officers participating in the roster of rapidly deployable personnel.
It is therefore necessary, as noted above, that such personnel have relevant United Nations experience.
It was envisaged that, when not deployed, the rapidly deployable mission headquarters would also maintain a database on all pre-selected personnel and would assist the training unit in its training of selected standby forces.
Upon further review of this training function, it has been determined that there would, indeed, have been some potential for overlap between the work of the rapidly deployable mission headquarters and the training unit.
This risk would be overcome with the revised system for rapid deployment, as the personnel would remain in their home country.
The present review addresses the General Assembly's request that the Secretariat further develop the concept of the rapidly deployable mission headquarters.
It is envisaged that the new concept would overcome a number of shortcomings inherent in the old concept: (a) unlike the previous system, the revised system would be designed for the maximum flexibility necessary to meet the wide range of personnel requirements of today's peacekeeping operations; (b) unlike the rapidly deployable mission headquarters, which could only be used for one mission at a time, the revised concept would allow for rapid deployment to more than one mission at any given time; (c) the revised system would be more cost-effective in that four, instead of eight posts, would be required; and (d) the revised system would also overcome the inherent constraint of the previous system in that, for political and security considerations, one or more staff in tier one of the rapidly deployable mission headquarters might not have been able to be deployed in a given mission area.
It must be stressed, however, that the success of the revised system would require the active commitment and participation of Member States and relevant organizations.
B. Administrative and budgetary issues
During the 2000/01 period, the Secretariat intends to address a number of administrative and budgetary issues relating to the backstopping of peacekeeping operations at Headquarters, focusing on four priority areas:
(a) A comprehensive review and updating of the Standard Cost Manual for Peacekeeping Operations;
(b) Development of standardized inventory reports that would provide review bodies, in particular, the Advisory Committee on Administrative and Budgetary Questions, with meaningful, timely information in a transparent, user-friendly format;
(c) Review of the current start-up kit concept of the United Nations Logistics Base at Brindisi in view of the recent upsurge in peacekeeping operations.
The review exercise will examine the existing arrangements in terms of the number and/or composition of the two existing start-up kits as well as the alternative possibility of advance acquisition of certain items of equipment with long delivery times, to be held as reserve stock at the Base;
(d) A review will also be made of the distribution of functional responsibilities between Headquarters and the field.
The level of the resources required and proposed for the next period has been assessed taking into consideration the developments described in the preceding paragraphs.
