Functions
The Office of the Under-Secretary-General directs and controls United Nations peacekeeping operations on behalf of the Secretary-General and formulates policies for peacekeeping operations and operational guidelines based on Security Council mandates.
The Office maintains open communications with Member States on all facets of peacekeeping.
In addition, it maintains liaison with the office of the Spokesman for the Secretary-General and the Department of Public Information and maintains extensive contacts with the media.
In order to promote understanding of United Nations peacekeeping, the staff attend seminars and conferences organized by Governments, intergovernmental organizations and academic institutions.
The Office comprises the immediate Office of the Under-Secretary-General, the Policy and Analysis and Lessons Learned Unit and the Executive Office.
The Policy and Analysis and Lessons Learned Unit acts as a think-tank to provide in-depth research and analyses of emergent questions related to peacekeeping policy, procedure and doctrine.
In addition to the various ad hoc requirements that arise regarding the review of texts and the maintenance of contact with external bodies working on issues of peace and security, priority items on the Unit's policy and analysis agenda can be divided into the following categories: long-term doctrinal research on issues and preparation or clarification of various operational guidelines; service to the Special Committee on Peacekeeping Operations and support to Member States' series of discussions on the use of police in peacekeeping; and fostering a coherent presentation of peacekeeping policy through provision of inputs to reports and participation in interdepartmental working groups, etc.
With regard to work on doctrine and guidelines, the Unit is exploring such issues as assistance by peacekeeping operations to civilians in armed conflict; guidelines for cooperation between peacekeeping operations and humanitarian and human rights elements; and the role of peacekeeping in disarmament, demobilization and reintegration.
In servicing the Special Committee on Peacekeeping Operations, the Unit, inter alia, provides relevant Secretariat reports, drafts speaking notes, organizes administrative aspects and prepares the text of the Special Committee's report.
With regard to Member States' discussion of the role of police in peacekeeping, the Unit's role has included the formulation of objectives and agendas, preparation of reports and coordination of follow-up.
In terms of fostering a coherent presentation of peacekeeping policy, the Unit participates in such task forces and working groups as the Working Group on Disarmament, Demobilization and Reintegration of the Executive Committee on Humanitarian Affairs; the initiative on Coordinating Action on Small Arms; the Strategic Planning Network and the Reference Group of the Inter-Agency Standing Committee.
During the period from 1 July 1998 to 30 June 1999, the lessons learned programme of work comprised the following items:
(a) The study on disarmament, demobilisation and reintegration carried over from the previous year;
(b) A study on mine clearance in a peacekeeping environment;
(c) A project on the implementation of lessons learned from peacekeeping operations;
(d) A project on the summary of lessons learned from the United Nations Protection Force (UNPROFOR)/United Nations Peace Forces (UNPF);
(e) A study of post-United Nations Transition Group (UNTAG) Namibia;
(f) Strengthening the Lessons Learned Resource Centre.
As noted above, the disarmament, demobilization and reintegration study was completed in 1999, as was the project on the implementation of lessons learned from peacekeeping operations, which involved field research in Angola, Georgia and Sierra Leone.
The project on UNPROFOR/UNPF, as well as the studies on post-UNTAG Namibia and mine clearance have advanced and are expected to be completed in 2000.
With regard to the item on strengthening the Lessons Learned Resource Centre, considerable progress has been made with the acquisition of research materials, the development of a database linking ongoing missions, and with the computerization of all resource materials, taking into account the recommendations of the Office of Internal Oversight Services.
The following items featured in the lessons learned work programme for the period from 1 July 1999 to 30 June 2000:
(a) A project on the application of lessons learned in the field;
(b) A study of lessons learned from civilian police operations in United Nations peacekeeping operations;
(c) A study of lessons learned from mine clearance operations in peacekeeping;
(d) A study on mainstreaming a gender perspective in peacekeeping operations;
(e) The study on post-UNTAG Namibia;
(f) Strengthening the Lessons Learned Resource Centre;
(g) A project on the implementation of the principles and guidelines of the disarmament, demobilization and reintegration study, in close cooperation with the Training Unit.
The Executive Office provides financial, personnel and administrative support services to the Department, including responsibility for financial management and performance reporting.
The work of the Executive Office continues to be characterized by the heavy workload relating to the recruitment and placement of staff.
