Functions
The Office of Operations provides executive direction for the implementation of Security Council mandates that establish peacekeeping operations and/or direct the Secretary-General to plan them.
The overall role of the Office of Operations is to act as a dynamic factor in devising, promoting agreement on and implementing solutions to the problems that arise in its area of responsibility.
The ease or difficulty in fulfilling this responsibility depends on a number of factors, including the nature of an operation's mandate, the willingness of the parties to peacefully resolve their dispute and cooperate with the United Nations in carrying out Security Council mandates and the willingness of other parties (regional organizations, interested Member States, etc.) to play their role through the provision of political support, manpower, logistics and the financial resources necessary for the implementation of the peace process.
The upsurge in peacekeeping over the past year has posed significant challenges to the Department of Peacekeeping Operations, including the Office of Operations.
The new operations in Kosovo and East Timor have been given unprecedented mandates in terms of executive authority for governance.
Moreover, institution-building activities have become an integral part of many peacekeeping operations.
These tasks have generated new types of challenges in planning, deploying and managing peacekeeping operations.
To help support the implementation of these tasks, in accordance with General Assembly resolution 54/243 of 23 December 1999, additional staff resources were provided to the Office in late 1999 to assist with the planning and management of such activities.
The Office of Operations leads the planning process by providing the overall framework, developing options for courses of action, leading reconnaissance missions to the field and coordinating and integrating inputs from within the Department and from other entities (e.g., military, police, humanitarian, electoral, human rights and such other aspects as logistics, support and staffing requirements) into a comprehensive plan for approval by the Security Council.
The Office has also supported the work of the International Commission of Inquiry in Rwanda and continues to compile information for, and deal with frequent requests from, the International Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia.
It also prepares briefings and responds to ad hoc requests for reports and information by the Security Council, the General Assembly, the Secretary-General, national Governments and other international bodies.
The Office is led by an Assistant Secretary-General and is comprised of three regional divisions (Africa Division, Europe and Latin America Division, and Asia and Middle East Division) and the Situation Centre.
The Assistant Secretary-General, and his front office, is responsible for coordinating the work of the Office of Operations and providing advice on policy and operational issues.
The workload of this office has increased significantly in the past year as a result of the overall upsurge in peacekeeping activities.
The establishment of UNAMSIL on 22 October 1999 and MONUC on 30 November 1999 and their subsequent expansions under Security Council resolutions 1289 (2000) and 1291 (2000), respectively, have further intensified the heavy workload of the Africa Division.
These missions have come at a time when the United Nations Mission for the Referendum in Western Sahara (MINURSO) is again facing difficulties in the implementation of the settlement plan.
The Division is still handling residual issues related to Angola.
It is also leading and coordinating contingency planning for a possible operation to help settle the conflict between Eritrea and Ethiopia; and is intensifying activities to strengthen African capacity for peacekeeping and cooperation with the Organization of African Unity (OAU).
In addition, staff continue to follow up on numerous issues related to former United Nations operations in Rwanda, Liberia, Somalia and other issues, including queries from Member States, parliaments, international commissions of inquiry and journalists.
All the missions in Africa are multidimensional peacekeeping operations, many of them located in areas of extreme volatility where, as in other regions, the wounds of war are still fresh and where the parties do not yet have the necessary trust to cooperate fully in the implementation of their mandates.
Security for United Nations staff in such areas is often poor, requiring a constant and vigilant watch and close consultation by Headquarters.
Again, because these are multidimensional operations, they require a great deal of consultation and coordination with the United Nations, the World Bank, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and bilateral partners.
Another complicating characteristic of these operations is that they have to deal with numerous parties on the ground whose positions are constantly shifting and have loose chains of command.
To illustrate the workload involved in the above, during 1999, UNOMSIL, followed by UNAMSIL, required over 300, often lengthy, substantive cables to provide the necessary guidance; 11 meetings with troop contributors, numerous briefings of the Security Council, 40 briefing notes for the Secretary-General and other high-level officials.
This is in addition to unrecorded daily telephone and e-mail communications.
The recently established mission in the Democratic Republic of the Congo, MONUC, is also a complex mission to manage, as there are over nine parties to the conflict.
This requires the preparation of highly sensitive guidance for the field and recommendations for the Secretary-General.
In the second half of 1999, over 35 background notes to the Secretary-General were prepared; numerous briefing notes were drafted for the Security Council; and over 300 cables were sent to the field to provide substantive guidance, as well as other numerous communications.
The Europe and Latin America Division is responsible for some of the most active peacekeeping operations (UNMIK, the United Nations Mission in Bosnia and Herzegovina (UNMIBH), the United Nations Observer Mission in Georgia (UNOMIG), the United Nations Mission of Observers in Prevlaka (UNMOP) and MIPONUH).
UNMIK, for example, is an unprecedented operation both in terms of its mandate and structure.
The complexity and volume of issues to be addressed on a daily basis generates the heaviest workload in the Division.
The United Nations has essentially been mandated to provide an interim administration for the territory of Kosovo, Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
The structure of the Mission is also unique in terms of its cooperative arrangements with regional organizations, which head some of its pillars under the authority of the Special Representative of the Secretary-General.
The Mission is highly political, commanding the constant attention of the Security Council.
The management of the Mission involves a great deal of consultation with the Secretary-General and the Deputy Secretary-General, as well as consultation and coordination at a senior level with regional organizations (European Union, the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)), United Nations agencies and other departments of the Secretariat.
Regular discussions with the Office of Legal Affairs are required to address the unprecedented and very difficult legal issues facing UNMIK.
In the six months between the Mission's establishment and the end of the year, the Division drafted over 400 cables to UNMIK, providing guidance and soliciting information; it also prepared some 200 background notes to the Secretary-General and other officials, and participated in 37 meetings with the Secretary-General and the Deputy Secretary-General and briefed the Security Council, donor countries, and other support groups on a weekly, and sometimes daily, basis.
In terms of workload statistics, the establishment of UNMIK has more than doubled the work of the Division.
In addition to its mission-related work, the Division was responsible in 1999 for preparing the report to the General Assembly on Srebrenica (A/54/549).
It is foreseen that the workload connected with the other missions for which the Division is responsible, in particular UNMOP, UNOMIG and UNMIBH, will remain active in the year ahead.
Given recent political developments affecting UNMOP, additional activity in regard to the role of the Chief Military Observer and the related coordination at Headquarters with the Permanent Missions to the United Nations concerned is anticipated, which, it is hoped, will lead to progress in the implementation of the Mission's mandate.
The situation in UNOMIG is likely to remain unstable, given political and security developments in the region, and will continue to require the full attention of the Division.
UNMIBH is currently one of the largest peacekeeping operations, with a number of multidimensional functions.
Its mandate is implemented in close cooperation with other organizations and continues to command the attention of Member States and is closely scrutinized by the Security Council.
This Mission will continue to require close monitoring and coordination at the senior level.
The expected termination of MIPONUH in the coming months and the sensitive work associated with this process — in particular the consultations leading to the establishment of a new mission in Haiti — will also continue to demand the close attention of the Division.
Of the eight operations in the Asia and Middle East Division, five were established around the most long-standing and intractable conflicts in the history of United Nations peacekeeping.
In the coming year, it is foreseen that the three missions in the Arab-Israeli theatre, the United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL), the United Nations Disengagement Observer Force (UNDOF), and the United Nations Truce Supervision Organization (UNTSO), will see more activity, especially if the resumed negotiations result in agreement.
In the Kashmir region, new military activity between India and Pakistan has meant a state of continuous high-alert for the United Nations Military Observer Group in India and Pakistan (UNMOGIP).
In Cyprus, the Secretary-General's initiatives in pursuing a durable solution are concomitant with a more pro-active role for the United Nations Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP) in facilitating community relations on the island through its peacekeeping functions.
These five missions, and the United Nations Iraq-Kuwait Observation Mission (UNIKOM), will continue to contribute to stability in their frequently volatile regions.
The Division's workload increased dramatically with the establishment of UNTAET, which has overall responsibility for the administration of East Timor, and is empowered to exercise all legislative and executive authority, including the administration of justice.
It is responsible for the full scope of government functions, which encompass the development of civil and social services, the provision of security and the maintenance of law and order; and the coordination and delivery of humanitarian assistance, rehabilitation and development assistance.
UNTAET is responsible for the training and creation of an East Timorese civil service and a civilian police force.
The Department of Peacekeeping Operations has the lead within the Secretariat for cooperation and coordination with and among the United Nations agencies, the Bretton Woods institutions and donor countries, a responsibility which is performed by the Division through the Task Force on East Timor, interdepartmental daily working-level meetings, and numerous ad hoc meetings in varying configurations.
In addition, there are frequent meetings with Member States individually and in groups.
The Security Council is kept constantly abreast of developments.
The Mission commands high-level interest among Member States and, in the Secretariat, the highest levels are closely involved.
The Situation Centre is responsible for expediting the information flows generated in the field to those responsible in the department, maintaining around-the-clock communications links with all missions, maintaining a crisis management capability and a task force area capable of operating at very short notice.
It also maintains and provides factual information to those in the Department of Peacekeeping Operations involved in peacekeeping planning and operational functions.
For instance, it provides background reports from open sources on the history of a conflict, as well as information on the existing infrastructure and geographic and socio-economic factors related to a possible mission area, which assist in the planning process.
During the past year, the demands on the Situation Centre's services increased rapidly with the establishment of UNMIK, UNTAET, UNAMSIL and MONUC.
For instance, over the past year, the calls received in connection with its 24-hour point of contact for peacekeeping operations increased from 70,000 to 80,000.
The Centre also increased the number of daily reports it produces on specific missions, in particular UNMIK and UNTAET, a service that was introduced in 1998.
Over the past year, some 270 such reports were produced, compared with 30 in 1998.
Another significant development in the work of the Centre over the past year was the introduction of video-conferencing.
The Centre facilitated a total of 96 such conferences in 1999.
