The workload statistics for the Office of Operations for the year 1999 reflect the complexity of peacekeeping mandates, especially those of the missions established during the past year.
Multifunctional tasks, addressing a variety of sectoral needs, continue to be an integral part of peacekeeping operations.
The mandates of two of the four multidimensional missions established in the past year — UNMIK and UNTAET — are even broader, including executive authority for governance.
These operations are deployed in areas of civil conflict, which could remain highly volatile.
Given the complexity of their mandates and the sensitivities of the peace process, the Security Council remains actively interested in them, requesting a constant flow of information from the Department of Peacekeeping Operations.
For instance, in the past year, the Department provided almost twice as many oral briefings to the Security Council as it had in 1998 (167 briefings in 1999, compared with 92 in 1998).
Given their nature, the management of these operations also requires very tight coordination within the United Nations system with interested Member States, contributors and donors.
The United Nations cannot implement broad multidimensional mandates on its own.
The Secretariat must call upon others who have the specialized knowledge required to assist in their implementation.
The World Bank and IMF are called upon in the areas of fiscal and economic development; the United Nations specialized agencies and programmes, including the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP), the Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), the World Trade Organization (WTO), the International Trade Organization (ITO) and the International Labour Organization (ILO), etc., all have a contribution to make in accordance with their various mandates.
Close cooperation with regional organizations such as OSCE, European Union, OAU, NATO and the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) is also required.
Bringing the various agencies and organizations into the structure of a peacekeeping operation, under the overall authority of the Special Representative of the Secretary-General, requires constant interaction to ensure the best possible contribution to the political, peace-building and development process.
Such coordination is the responsibility of the Office of Operations.
It is achieved primarily through interdepartmental and inter-agency meetings, as well as meetings with interested Member States, where needs and problems are discussed and consensus on issues reached.
This is reflected in the workload statistics of the Office.
The number of task forces, consisting of various Secretariat departments and United Nations agencies, either chaired by the Department of Peacekeeping Operations or in which the Department participated, more than doubled in the past year, from 146 in 1998 to 297 in 1999.
During the past year, the Department began holding video-conferences to bring together, through the Situation Centre facilities, representatives of various departments and agencies in New York, Geneva and Rome with counterparts from the missions, for daily or weekly coordination and policy-making meetings; 96 such video-conferences were held during the year.
The use of crisis action teams — to share information at the interdepartmental working level and with Member States, especially during times of crisis — also rose, from 35 in 1998 to 60 in 1999.
These statistics show that an assessment of the work of the Office of Operations cannot be captured on the basis of written output alone.
One must also look at the considerable time and work that goes into coordinating the development of procedures, policies and operational guidance required to properly manage the type of operations that have been established in recent years.
