Unlike the other Divisions, which are headed by Directors at the D-2 level, the post for the head of the Europe and Latin America Division is currently graded at the D-1 level.
This anomaly is owing to historical reasons.
Until the end of 1995, the Division was responsible for the operations in Central America, Haiti and Georgia, but all the activities of the Department of Peacekeeping Operations relating to the Balkans (essentially UNPROFOR) were handled directly by the Office of the Under-Secretary-General for Peacekeeping Operations.
With the termination of UNPROFOR and the signing of the Dayton Agreement, responsibility for the new missions in the region (UNMIBH, UNMOP, the United Nations Preventive Deployment Force (UNPREDEP) and the United Nations Transitional Administration for Eastern Slavonia, Baranja and Western Sirmium (UNTAES)) was placed with the Division.
This led to a tremendous increase in the Division's workload and responsibilities and would have amply justified upgrading the post of Director to the D-2 level; however, this could not be achieved at that time.
As noted above, the establishment of UNMIK in 1999 has meant a further qualitative and quantitative increase in the workload of the Division and has added to the already significant political and managerial responsibilities carried out by the Acting Director.
Hence, the need to correct this anomaly has now become more acute.
The D-1 post in the Division is funded under the regular budget.
For the reasons stated above, it is requested that the General Assembly approve, on an exceptional basis, the upgrading of the D-1 post under the regular budget for the Division to the D-2 level effective 1 July 2000.
At the present time, no additional resources are being requested under the regular budget in connection with this proposal.
Additional requirements would be addressed in the context of the first performance report for the programme budget for the biennium 2000-2001.
Office of Logistics Management and Mine Action
Posts
Functions
The Office of Logistics Management and Mine Action provides executive direction and overall coordination of all logistics and administration activities for field missions, including staffing, administration, finance and procurement.
The Office is led by an Assistant Secretary-General and consists of the Field Administration and Logistics Division and the Mine Action Service.
The Field Administration and Logistics Division translates operation plans into support plans and implements the plans.
Support functions typically encompass some 25 discrete areas of activity, most of which require specialized skills. These areas of activity are: communications; electronic data-processing; the field asset control system; contract administration; vehicle fleet management; air support; air safety; movement control; shipment; supplies (water, fuel, food, accoutrements); services contracts; logistic operations; medical support; pouch, mail and administrative services; engineering (infrastructure, prefabs, construction); power generation; water and sanitation; operational demining; staff administration; recruitment; travel; claims; budgets and budget performance; finance management; regulatory framework; and standard operating procedures.
Normally, a surge in activities flowing from the establishment of a new mission affects the performance of some or all of the above areas.
When the surge in activity is owing to the establishment of a large operation requiring a major effort, most of the activities related to older missions are deferred, resulting either in an increased backlog or in reduced oversight, aggravated by the fact that such missions may have lost key personnel in favour of the newly established ones.
As a result of the upsurge in the peacekeeping activities in 1999, the support requirements also increased manifold.
This is a result not only of the sharp increase in the volume of field missions' budgets, numbers of staff and troops, civilian police and military observers, but also because of the growing complexity of the mandates of the new operations.
Consequently, the Division's capacity needs to be enhanced in order to meet additional workload and ensure efficient handling of the whole range of resultant complex logistics and administrative issues.
The Field Administration and Logistics Division consists of three organizational units in addition to the Office of the Director: the Finance Management and Support Service, the Logistics and Communications Service and the Personnel Management and Support Service.
The Office of the Director of the Field Administration and Logistics Division provides overall management, orientation and coordination of the work of the Division.
It initiates reviews by the services of the regulatory framework, including policies, processes and procedures; reviews and approves various initiatives to enhance the capacity and preparedness of the Division to mount field operations and manage them efficiently; maintains liaison with other entities within and outside the Department, as well as with Member States and legislative bodies and participates in intergovernmental meetings.
The Office manages the resources of the Division, ensures that accountability and internal control measures are in place and establishes and reviews requirements for programme monitoring and evaluation.
It coordinates and integrates activities of the Division's organizational units on inter-service issues and issues of concern for all peacekeeping operations.
The Finance Management and Support Service provides financial management and support services to peacekeeping, peacemaking and preventive diplomacy operations and trust funds related to peacekeeping and peacemaking activities from start-up through closure and liquidation.
The Logistics and Communications Service provides the multifaceted interface between plans, mandates and budgets on the one hand, and the practicalities of mounting, sustaining, communicating with and liquidating actual peacekeeping missions on the other.
The Service's tasks are correspondingly complex and varied.
The Logistics and Communications Service is responsible for the development of logistics and communications doctrine and policy, and the provision of expert advice and operational guidance to the field missions on all transport, supply, engineering, communications and electronic data-processing matters.
The Service also develops and maintains the Department's logistics readiness measures to support new or expanding field missions, including the mission start-up kits and the Field Administration and Logistics Division Reserve held at the United Nations Logistics Base at Brindisi.
It develops plans for logistics support for new or expanding field missions. The Service conducts technical survey missions, specifying equipment, supplies and services, assists in determining financial implications for such missions, and dispatches logistics implementation teams to oversee the critical start-up period for new missions.
The Service determines the need for construction projects; assesses requirements for renovation and development of military and civilian living and working accommodation, water and fuel supply and storage, sanitation and electricity generation in field missions; assesses missions' communications, electronic data-processing, surface transport and air transport requirements, and operates the United Nations aviation safety programme; arranges strategic transport of troops and equipment to and from missions, by air and sea; is responsible for the design, implementation and maintenance of the Department's computerized global matériel management database, the field mission logistics control system; provides specialist medical advice for peacekeeping operations; manages the supply of medical goods and services for the Department; determines the method of supply for field mission requirements; and ensures that these requirements are met by transferring assets between missions (including the Field Administration and Logistics Division Reserve), raising requisitions for commercial procurement action, or issuing letters of assist for supply by a Member State.
The Service prepares detailed technical and contractual specifications and proposals for the supply of required goods and services.
It evaluates bids and proposals based on technical criteria, timeliness of delivery and other relevant logistics support aspects.
Logistics and Communications Service also provides logistics evaluation of the contingent-owned equipment and self-sustainment proposals of troop-contributing countries for new and existing missions, and trains field mission staff in the preparation and certification of contingent-owned equipment verification reports, and verifies Contingents' performance against the relevant contingent-owned equipment memoranda of understanding for reimbursement to the troop-contributing country.
The Service prepares statements of work for new contracts, manages signed contracts and letters of assist for the provision of logistics goods and services, and Service section chiefs now act as global asset managers for their specialist ranges of equipment, and have certifying authority for all purchases made against United Nations Headquarters global contracts.
The Personnel Management and Support Service is responsible for anticipating, identifying and meeting the civilian personnel requirements of field missions and ensuring their efficient deployment, management, administration and separation.
The Service plays an important role in the full lifespan of a mission, from planning to implementation and liquidation.
During the budgetary period, the Service remained engaged in identification and determination of staffing requirements for field missions, monitoring and managing of staffing tables, posts and vacancies; review, selection, appointment and assignment of all international civilian staff; arranging travel to field missions for all international civilian personnel, military observers and civilian police; administration of contracts, salaries and benefits for all international civilian staff serving in field missions; processing initial appointment, assignment, extension and separation of the staff members serving in the field; monitoring mission administration of locally recruited staff; implementation of the Integrated Management Information System (IMIS), development and maintenance of information management systems throughout the Service and in coordination with field missions; advising missions on general information for field administration and personnel policy and assisting in interpretation of staff rules and administrative issuances; contributing to development of organizational personnel policy, including participation in human resources management task forces and working groups, and conducting staff management consultations on personnel policies applicable to field missions; developing and maintaining up-to-date rosters of applicants for priority occupational groups; development, implementation and management of career development, including learning and training programmes for field mission personnel; development and management of a staff welfare programme by ensuring substantive, psychological and medical preparedness of deployed personnel and adequate stress management through development of policies, such as occasional recuperation breaks, conducive to health and well-being of staff; maintaining liaison with the United Nations Security Coordinator on administrative measures relating to security and safety of field personnel; undertaking all necessary notification and administrative arrangements in respect of civilian injuries and casualties in the field; and undertaking visits to the field as necessary for mission planning, start-up, support and monitoring and assessment of the exercise of delegated authority.
The Mine Action Service is the focal point within the United Nations system for all landmine-related issues.
The Service is responsible for the development of policies, procedures, standards and technical guidelines for all aspects of mine action, including clearance, dangerous area reduction and mine awareness in support of field missions authorized by the Security Council.
The Service participates in pre-mission planning and in-theater assessment, the establishment of the mine action coordination function and ongoing quality assurance monitoring.
In 1999, the Service responded to Security Council requirements for the establishment of the mine action capacity in Kosovo and Sierra Leone as well as assessment of the mine action situation in the Democratic Republic of the Congo.
In 2000, it is anticipated that a mine action response will be required for Ethiopia, Eritrea, Western Sahara and Guinea-Bissau among other possible missions.
