An estimated $389,000 is required to fund training activities carried out by the Department's Training Unit:
(a) Train the trainers.
The United Nations training courses for military and civilian police national trainers on peacekeeping, human rights and humanitarian assistance are held jointly with the Centre for Human Rights, UNHCR and the United Nations Staff College in Turin, Italy.
Subsequent courses will be limited to one per year in Turin and another in a country willing to host the same, as a means of keeping knowledge of peacekeeping activities current and of offering refresher courses.
New subject matters such as gender mainstreaming and a more comprehensive presentation on the acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS)/human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) introduced in the last course.
Lecturers with peacekeeping experience as well as previous students of the course are being utilized to better prepare future trainers of national contingents that are to be deployed to peacekeeping missions;
(b) United Nations training assistance team seminars.
The seminars, first introduced four years ago, have proved to be an effective means of having training advisers on standby, ready for deployment to any Member State in need of peacekeeping training assistance.
There are currently 200 members of this team from over 100 Member States in all regions.
Active membership, however, is limited to two years, during and after which courses will be conducted in each region to train new members.
This will ensure the infusion of fresh knowledge and experience.
Furthermore, as more and more countries express a desire to participate, either for the first time or in an increased capacity in peacekeeping missions, the need to conduct more courses in various regions has become imperative;
(c) Simulation peacekeeping operations exercises.
Member States involved in simulation exercises, which are usually participated in by multinational contingents, frequently seek the assistance of the Training Unit in providing a programme syllabus, accreditation, lecturers and other participants to the event.
This type of exercise provides hands-on experience with real-time scenarios of a peacekeeping environment being acted out by the participants.
Positive feedback from peacekeepers who have benefited from this kind of exercises has increased the demand and a number of Member States have expressed the desire to host the exercises;
(d) Peacekeeping operations workshops and training assistance to Member States.
Various national and regional peacekeeping training centres have worked in close cooperation with the Training Unit over the years and continue to conduct training courses on a regular basis.
The Department of Peacekeeping Operations participation is essential to ensure the uniformity of content and standards, as well as to reiterate the United Nations commitment to enhancing the peacekeeping capacity of countries where it is requested;
There is now a requirement to include training in cultural and gender sensitivity in future mission readiness training programmes.
Adequate resources are necessary to conduct pre-deployment training tailored to particular missions, especially as new ones are under way.
