Operational plan and requirements
The 1999/00 budget of MONUA contained in the report of the Secretary-General dated 5 May 1999 (A/53/937) was predicated on the early completion of consultations with the Government of Angola regarding the follow-up configuration of the United Nations presence in the country upon expiration of its mandate on 26 February 1999, and on the termination of liquidation activities in the mission area by 31 October 1999, in accordance with the projections indicated in paragraph 33 of the report of the Secretary-General to the Security Council dated 24 February 1999 (S/1999/202).
Developments on the ground during the period from July to October 1999, however, had resulted in substantial unforeseen adjustments to the original budget assumptions.
Pending the conclusion of consultations with the Government of Angola, and until the subsequent establishment by the Security Council in its resolution 1268 (1999) of 15 October 1999 of the United Nations Office in Angola, the substantive MONUA personnel required to maintain liaison with the political, military, police and other civilian authorities of Angola, as well as its human rights component, were retained in the country as part of the Observer Mission's staffing establishment.
Moreover, the Mission was obliged to enter into and continue protracted negotiations with the Government of Angola regarding disposition of the substantial amount of assets valued at $38.1 million remaining in the country after the transfer of equipment to other peacekeeping operations and United Nations Logistics Base at Brindisi. For that reason, the necessary administrative and technical personnel, military security detachment and logistical support services were also required to continue beyond the originally projected deadlines, resulting in unforeseen additional resource requirements.
As a result, the resources appropriated by the General Assembly in its resolution 53/228 for the liquidation of MONUA have proved to be insufficient.
